Introduction:¶

In this project, at first, we inspected data and prepared and normalized it for implementing learning algorithms on it. The next step was to enhance and set hyperparameters of each algorithm to get the maximum accuracy from each model and in the final step we test group learning algorithms to check if they improve our models or not.

Question:¶

In order to predict if a customer returns back to a shop, we need to build a model using machine learning algorithms. First we train the model using the given dataset. This data set consists of customer ID, total quantity, total price, country, date, whether the customer came back and purchase count.

Before anything we import libraries that are needed in the project:

Now we modify the data by erasing rows with invalid values and useless columns like customer id and convert country column using one hot encoding. If we want to use categorical data we should convert it to numeric data. One approach is to use One Hot encoding that adds a column for each word and determins that category by 0 and 1 values but this method have a negative point which is that we have to add one column for each word available so we will need a lot of memory so we can't use it for many columns or a column that has a lot of possible values. Other approach is to use label encoding in which each category will be labeled with an integer bigger than 0 but the problem is that different categories will get different numeric numbers and the model would be trained based on this value which is not desired so we use one hot encoding in this project.

The final step of data preproccessing is scaling usefull values using Minmaxscaler. In most of the machine learning algorithms, we have to scale data in order to prevent one big number impacting the model more than it is supposed to. In this project MinMaxScaler is used which reduces minimum value of each column from all values in each column divide it by max - min so that all values are between 0 and 1.

Decision Tree:¶

After the preproccessing stage we start implementing learning algorithms. First one is decision tree. A decision tree is a decision support tool that uses a tree-like model of decisions and their possible consequences, including chance event outcomes, resource costs, and utility. It is one way to display an algorithm that only contains conditional control statements. The best way to show the effect of depth is to show metrics plot. It could be seen that when the depth is increased more than a threshold overfitting happens because the leaves of the tree will contain less nodes and the model will be trained to give better answers for the trained data but worse for test data. The accuracy starts to decrease from depth of 4. The depth I chose is 5 because all metrics are high enough.

In [32]:

KNN:¶

K-Nearest-Neighbors algorithm (kNN) is a non-parametric method used for classification and regression. In both cases, the input consists of the k closest training examples in the feature space. The output depends on whether k-NN is used for classification or regression. The number of neighbors that is considered will affect accuracy and recall and precision significntly. The best number was 16 for me. If you increase it more than this overfitting will happen that will make our results invalid.

Random Forest:¶

Random forests or random decision forests are an ensemble learning method for classification, regression and other tasks that operate by constructing a multitude of decision trees at training time and outputting the class that is the mode of the classes or mean prediction of the individual trees. Random decision forests correct for decision trees' habit of overfitting to their training set. Combining predictions from multiple models works better than baggng if the predictions from the submodels are uncorrelated. Random Forest has 2 hyperparameters: Depth and number of estimators. Increasing the depth to some threshold will increase the accuracy but after that overfitting will occur and discredits our model. Increasing the number of estimators will also increase the accuracy but it has a threshold like depth. The best values are 20 for depth and 36 for number of estimators. It could be seen that only recall increases.

Impact of Bagging on overfitting and Bootstrapping:¶

We can see that bagging decreases the effect of overfitting. Bagging takes the advantage of ensemble learning multiple weak learners and it helps to reduce variance and as a result of that helps us avoid overfitting. Bootstrapping is a sampling technique in which it chooses k samples from n samples with replacement and the we run algorithm on each of these samples. Bootstrapping improves bias and reduces variance. If we have done sampling without replacement the samples drawn will be dependent on the previous ones randomness of our data would be destroyed.

In [80]:

Conclusion:¶

At first all three methods of decision tree and knn and logistic regrssion accuracies and precisions and recalls were almost same. Random Forest method performed well but bagging didn't because we prevented overfitting at first phase and usage of bagging only increases bias. Hard Voting also made very little difference because as I said before the results from 3 methods were almost the same. At the end I cans say that none of the the ensemble learning methods improved our model in this dataset.
